# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# IDENTITY-BASED RATE LIMITING CONFIGURATION
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 
# DEPLOYMENT: Onsite CTF with 400 concurrent users behind shared NAT
# 
# CRITICAL DESIGN DECISIONS:
# 
# 1. PUBLIC ENDPOINTS (IP-based, very loose)
#    - Health checks, static assets, unauthenticated pages
#    - High limits because all 400 users share same IP
#    - Example: 2000 requests per 60 seconds = ~3 req/sec per user
# 
# 2. LOGIN ENDPOINT (email+IP composite)
#    - ONLY place where IP is used for authenticated flow
#    - Prevents account brute-force: attacker can't rotate IPs to bypass
#    - Prevents spray attacks: can't try 1000 emails from same NAT
#    - Isolates failures: user1@ctf failing doesn't block user2@ctf
#    - After 5 failures in 5min, account locked for 15min from that IP
# 
# 3. GENERAL API (email from JWT)
#    - Pure identity-based: 400 users behind NAT = no collisions
#    - Scoreboard refresh, challenge list, profile, teams
#    - 60 requests per 60 seconds = 1 req/sec (allows rapid scoreboard refresh)
# 
# 4. FLAG SUBMISSION (email+challengeID)
#    - Per-challenge isolation: can't exhaust attempts globally
#    - 3 attempts per 60 seconds per challenge
#    - After 10 total failures, challenge locked for 5min
#    - Cleared automatically on correct submission
# 
# 5. TOKEN REFRESH (refresh token ID)
#    - Per-token tracking: prevents refresh loops
#    - 10 refreshes per hour per token (normal = 1-2)
# 
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# PUBLIC ENDPOINTS (Unauthenticated, IP-based)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Use for: /health, /api/public/*, static assets

# Time window in seconds
PUBLIC_RL_WINDOW=60

# Max requests per window per IP (shared by all 400 users)
# Calculation: 400 users × 5 requests/min = 2000
PUBLIC_RL_LIMIT=2000

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# LOGIN ENDPOINT (email+IP composite key)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CRITICAL: Only endpoint using IP for authenticated users
# Composite key isolates brute-force per account per source

# Time window in seconds (5 minutes)
LOGIN_RL_WINDOW=300

# Max attempts per email+IP in window
# Allows 5 attempts = normal user might typo 2-3 times
LOGIN_RL_LIMIT=5

# Lockout time in seconds after limit exceeded (15 minutes)
# Prevents rapid retry after hitting limit
LOGIN_LOCK_TIME=900

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# GENERAL API ENDPOINTS (JWT email-based)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Use for: /api/challenges, /api/scoreboard, /api/teams, /api/profile

# Time window in seconds
API_RL_WINDOW=60

# Max requests per user per window
# Allows 1 request per second (aggressive scoreboard refresh)
API_RL_LIMIT=60

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FLAG SUBMISSION (email+challengeID composite)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Per-challenge rate limiting with failure lockout

# Time window in seconds
FLAG_RL_WINDOW=60

# Max submissions per challenge per user per window
# 3 attempts allows: quick typo fix, case sensitivity check
FLAG_RL_LIMIT=3

# Number of failed attempts before lockout
# 10 failures = clear brute-force attempt
FLAG_FAIL_LOCK=10

# Lockout time in seconds (5 minutes)
FLAG_LOCK_TIME=300

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# TOKEN REFRESH (refresh token ID)
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Prevents refresh token abuse and loops

# Time window in seconds (1 hour)
REFRESH_RL_WINDOW=3600

# Max refreshes per token per window
# Normal usage = 1-2 per hour (tokens last 15min-1hour)
# 10 allows legitimate reconnects without blocking
REFRESH_RL_LIMIT=10

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# PRODUCTION TUNING GUIDE
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 
# SCENARIO: Users report "too many requests" during CTF
# 
# STEP 1: Check Redis for blocked keys
#   redis-cli --scan --pattern "ctf:rl:*" | head -20
#   redis-cli get "ctf:rl:<key>"
# 
# STEP 2: Identify which limit is triggering
#   - Login errors → increase LOGIN_RL_LIMIT or decrease LOGIN_RL_WINDOW
#   - API errors → increase API_RL_LIMIT (currently 60/min = 1/sec)
#   - Flag errors → increase FLAG_RL_LIMIT (but beware brute force)
# 
# STEP 3: Emergency override (disable rate limiting)
#   Set all *_RL_LIMIT values to 999999
#   Restart backend: pm2 restart ecosystem.config.js
# 
# STEP 4: Clear all rate limits (nuclear option)
#   redis-cli --scan --pattern "ctf:rl:*" | xargs redis-cli DEL
# 
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# MONITORING & LOGGING
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 
# Rate limit events are logged with:
#   [RateLimit] Lockout set: <hashed-key> for <seconds>s - <reason>
#   [RateLimit] Cleared flag limit for <email> on challenge <id>
#   [RateLimit] Redis error in <function>: <error>
# 
# Monitor with:
#   pm2 logs | grep RateLimit
#   tail -f backend/server.log | grep RateLimit
# 
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# SECURITY NOTES
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 
# 1. All identity keys are SHA-256 hashed before Redis storage
#    - Prevents enumeration attacks on Redis
#    - Protects PII (emails) from Redis dump exposure
# 
# 2. Algorithm: Sliding window with Redis sorted sets
#    - More accurate than fixed window (no boundary issues)
#    - O(log N) complexity, effectively O(1) in practice
#    - Auto-expiry prevents memory leaks
# 
# 3. Fail-open strategy: If Redis down, allow requests
#    - Prevents total platform outage if Redis crashes
#    - Logged for monitoring/alerting
#    - Trade-off: temporary rate limit bypass vs availability
# 
# 4. No IP-based limits for authenticated routes (except login)
#    - Prevents NAT-induced false positives
#    - Each user isolated by email identity
# 
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
